WEBVTT

1
00:00:12.580 --> 00:00:14.100
You know who I'm envious of?
你们知道我最嫉妒谁吗？

2
00:00:14.940 --> 00:00:18.276
People who work in a job that has to do with their college major.
那些能找到和大学专业对口工作的人。

3
00:00:18.300 --> 00:00:20.196
(Laughter)
（笑声）

4
00:00:20.220 --> 00:00:22.796
Journalists who studied journalism,
新闻专业的记者，

5
00:00:22.820 --> 00:00:24.780
engineers who studied engineering.
工程学专业的工程师。

6
00:00:25.820 --> 00:00:28.155
The truth is, these folks are no longer the rule,
事实上，这些人的存在 早已不再是正常情况了，

7
00:00:27.870 --> 00:00:29.280
but the exception.
而成了例外。

8
00:00:29.460 --> 00:00:32.636
A 2010 study found that only a quarter of college graduates
2010年的一个调查显示 只有1/4的大学生，

9
00:00:32.660 --> 00:00:34.900
work in a field that relates to their degree.
在从事和他们大学专业相关的工作。

10
00:00:35.900 --> 00:00:39.740
I graduated with not one but two degrees in biology.
我毕业时拿到了生物学的双学位。

11
00:00:40.580 --> 00:00:44.356
To my parents' dismay, I am neither a doctor nor a scientist.
但令我父母失望的是，我既不是一个医生， 也没有成为一个科学家。

12
00:00:44.380 --> 00:00:46.396
(Laughter)
（笑声）

13
00:00:46.420 --> 00:00:49.516
Years of studying DNA replication and photosynthesis
在DNA复制与光合作用上 数年的专心苦读，

14
00:00:49.540 --> 00:00:52.180
did little to prepare me for a career in technology.
对我将来的科技生涯几乎没有帮助。

15
00:00:52.940 --> 00:00:57.276
I had to teach myself everything from sales, marketing, strategy,
我必须从销售，市场营销， 策略开始自学一切本领，

16
00:00:57.300 --> 00:00:59.700
even a little programming, on my own.
甚至连简单的电脑编程，都必须自学。

17
00:01:00.940 --> 00:01:03.356
I had never held the title of Product Manager
在我送简历到 Etsy（电子商务网站）之前，

18
00:01:03.380 --> 00:01:05.300
before I sent my resume in to Etsy.
我从来没当过产品经理。

19
00:01:06.700 --> 00:01:09.796
I had already been turned down by Google and several other firms
我当时十分沮丧， 因为已经被谷歌以及

20
00:01:09.820 --> 00:01:11.220
and was getting frustrated.
其他一些公司屡次拒绝。

21
00:01:11.580 --> 00:01:13.876
The company had recently gone public,
Etsy最近正式上市了，

22
00:01:13.900 --> 00:01:15.676
so as part of my job application,
为了让简历增色，

23
00:01:15.700 --> 00:01:19.276
I read the IPO filings from cover to cover
我把首次公开募股的信息 一行行认真地读，

24
00:01:19.300 --> 00:01:22.996
and built a website from scratch which included my analysis of the business
然后摸索着建立了一个网站，其中 包括一些我对这个公司的分析

25
00:01:23.020 --> 00:01:24.940
and four ideas for new features.
以及四个关于产品特色的新点子。

26
00:01:26.060 --> 00:01:29.596
It turned out the team was actively working on two of those ideas
结果发现这个公司的工作团队 积极地研究了其中两个，

27
00:01:29.620 --> 00:01:31.660
and had seriously considered a third.
并对第三个也进行了慎重考虑。

28
00:01:32.940 --> 00:01:34.180
I got the job.
于是我得到了这份工作。

29
00:01:36.380 --> 00:01:39.716
We all know people who were ignored or overlooked at first
我们都知道有些人 虽然一开始被忽略，

30
00:01:39.740 --> 00:01:41.740
but went on to prove their critics wrong.
但最终用实力证明了他人的错误。

31
00:01:42.580 --> 00:01:43.820
My favorite story?
我最爱的故事是什么呢？

32
00:01:44.900 --> 00:01:47.796
Brian Acton, an engineering manager
Brian Acton, 一个工程经理，

33
00:01:47.820 --> 00:01:50.676
who was rejected by both Twitter and Facebook
在成立whatsApp (聊天软件)之前，

34
00:01:50.700 --> 00:01:52.316
before cofounding WhatsApp,
他同时被谷歌和推特拒绝过，

35
00:01:52.340 --> 00:01:55.980
the mobile messaging platform that would sell for 19 billion dollars.
而现在这个手机软件 平台价值190亿。

36
00:01:57.620 --> 00:02:00.556
The hiring systems we built in the 20th century are failing us
我们在20世纪建立的 招聘系统已经过时了，

37
00:02:00.580 --> 00:02:03.860
and causing us to miss out on people with incredible potential.
这导致我们错失了很多 颇具潜力的人才。

38
00:02:05.140 --> 00:02:07.276
The advances in robotics and machine learning
机器人技术和机器学习的进步

39
00:02:06.890 --> 00:02:09.140
and transforming the way we work,
正在转变我们工作的方式，

40
00:02:09.300 --> 00:02:12.316
automating routine tasks in many occupations
把许多行业的日常事务自动化，

41
00:02:12.340 --> 00:02:16.420
while augmenting and amplifying human labor in others.
从而将人类的劳力转向其他方面。

42
00:02:17.260 --> 00:02:21.316
At this rate, we should all be expecting to do jobs we've never done before
这样下去，我们在 接下来的职业生涯中都要做

43
00:02:21.340 --> 00:02:22.859
for the rest of our careers.
从未做过的工作。

44
00:02:24.300 --> 00:02:26.676
So what are the tools and strategies we need
那么我们需要什么样的 工具以及技巧来辨别那些能够

45
00:02:26.700 --> 00:02:28.660
to identify tomorrow's high performers?
驰骋未来职场的人才呢？

46
00:02:29.620 --> 00:02:33.716
In search for answers, I've consulted with leaders across many sectors,
为了寻得答案，我和 许多部门的领导进行了探讨，

47
00:02:33.740 --> 00:02:36.356
read dozens of reports and research papers
读了很多报告和研究资料，

48
00:02:36.380 --> 00:02:39.100
and conducted some of my own talent experiments.
并分析了我自己的天赋与经历。

49
00:02:39.820 --> 00:02:41.716
My quest is far from over,
我的寻找还远没有结束，

50
00:02:41.740 --> 00:02:44.380
but here are three ideas to take forward.
但有三个要点值得一提。

51
00:02:45.100 --> 00:02:47.660
One: expand your search.
第一：扩展你的搜索范围。

52
00:02:48.098 --> 00:02:50.956
If we only look for talent in the same places we always do --
如果我们每次只去同样的地方 寻找自己的天赋——

53
00:02:50.980 --> 00:02:53.236
gifted child programs, Ivy League schools,
天才少年项目，常青藤名校，

54
00:02:53.260 --> 00:02:55.156
prestigious organizations --
那些盛名远扬的机构——

55
00:02:55.180 --> 00:02:57.796
we're going to get the same results we always have.
那我们只能得到一样的结果。

56
00:02:57.820 --> 00:03:01.516
Baseball was transformed when the cash-strapped Oakland Athletics
奥克兰的运动员队，由于囊中羞涩，

57
00:03:01.540 --> 00:03:03.916
started recruiting players who didn't score highly
只能聘用那些在传统标准， 如打点记录中，

58
00:03:03.940 --> 00:03:06.516
on traditionally valued metrics, like runs batted in,
虽然得分较低， 但却能够帮助队友得分，

59
00:03:06.540 --> 00:03:09.596
but who had the ability to help the team score points
并最终赢得比赛的球员，

60
00:03:09.620 --> 00:03:10.820
and win games.
而这最终导致了棒球的演变。

61
00:03:11.340 --> 00:03:13.460
This idea is taking hold outside of sports.
这道理在体育之外也同样适用。

62
00:03:14.300 --> 00:03:16.596
The Head of Design and Research at Pinterest
Pinterest研究与设计部门的 负责人和我说，

63
00:03:16.620 --> 00:03:18.996
told me that they've built one of the most diverse
他们在硅谷打造了一支，

64
00:03:19.020 --> 00:03:21.116
and high-performing teams in Silicon Valley
全世界最高效， 同时最具分化特色的团队。

65
00:03:21.140 --> 00:03:23.516
because they believe that no one type of person
因为他们相信没有哪一类特定的人

66
00:03:23.540 --> 00:03:25.380
holds a monopoly on talent.
具有垄断性的天赋才能。

67
00:03:26.260 --> 00:03:28.956
They've worked hard to look beyond major tech hubs
他们的眼光超越了核心科技，

68
00:03:28.980 --> 00:03:31.236
and focus on designers' portfolios,
并注重于设计者们的资历，

69
00:03:31.260 --> 00:03:32.580
not their pedigrees.
而不是他们的血统。

70
00:03:33.940 --> 00:03:36.300
Two: hire for performance.
第二：为了效率而雇佣

71
00:03:36.900 --> 00:03:39.156
Inspired by my own job experience,
受到我自己工作经历的启发，

72
00:03:39.180 --> 00:03:41.876
I cofounded a hiring platform called Headlight,
我和别人合建了一个 招聘平台Headlight，

73
00:03:41.900 --> 00:03:44.540
which gives candidates an opportunity to shine.
这个平台给了应聘者们 一个展示自我的机会。

74
00:03:45.180 --> 00:03:48.036
Just as teams have tryouts and plays have auditions,
就好似团队有路演， 乐队有试奏，

75
00:03:48.060 --> 00:03:50.636
candidates should be asked to demonstrate their skills
应聘者在被雇佣之前，

76
00:03:50.660 --> 00:03:52.076
before they're hired.
应该有展示自己技能的机会。

77
00:03:52.100 --> 00:03:55.476
Our clients are benefiting from 85 years of employment research,
从85年的职场雇佣研究资料里， 我们的客户可以看到

78
00:03:55.500 --> 00:03:57.076
which shows that work samples
预测职场成功与否的

79
00:03:57.100 --> 00:03:59.660
are one of the best predictors of success on the job.
最好方式就是工作实例。

80
00:04:00.620 --> 00:04:02.196
If you're hiring a data analyst,
如果你在招聘一个数据分析员，

81
00:04:02.220 --> 00:04:05.956
give them a spreadsheet of historical data and ask them for their key insights.
就给他们一张填满历史数据的 表格并要求他们给出解析。

82
00:04:05.980 --> 00:04:07.796
If you're hiring a marketing manager,
如果你在招聘一个市场经理，

83
00:04:07.820 --> 00:04:10.236
have them plan a launch campaign for a new product.
就让他们计划一场新产品的发布会。

84
00:04:10.260 --> 00:04:13.436
And if you're a candidate, don't wait for an employer to ask.
而如果你是一个应聘者， 别等着老板询问你。

85
00:04:13.460 --> 00:04:17.716
Seek out ways to showcase your unique skills and abilities
寻找能够展现你的独特技巧 与能力的方式，

86
00:04:17.740 --> 00:04:20.220
outside of just the standard resume and cover letter.
而不仅仅是依赖于简历以及推荐信。

87
00:04:20.860 --> 00:04:23.900
Three: get the bigger picture.
第三：着眼全局

88
00:04:24.460 --> 00:04:27.996
I've heard about recruiters who are quick to label a candidate a job-hopper
我见过招聘人员不假思索的给一个 应聘者贴上“跳槽者”的标签，

89
00:04:27.740 --> 00:04:30.386
based on a single short stint on their resume;
仅仅是因为他的简历上 有一项短期的工作；

90
00:04:30.740 --> 00:04:34.980
read about professors who are more likely to ignore identical messages from students
我也听说不少教授会因为 学生的名字属于黑人或亚洲人，

91
00:04:36.140 --> 00:04:39.860
because their name was black or Asian instead of white.
就忽视他们发送的和 白人学生一模一样的消息。

92
00:04:40.660 --> 00:04:43.140
I was almost put on a special needs track as a child.
我小时候几乎被当成有 “特殊需要”的孩子。

93
00:04:43.940 --> 00:04:45.556
A month into kindergarten,
进入幼儿园一个月后，

94
00:04:45.580 --> 00:04:47.196
my teacher wrote a page-long memo
我的老师记录了一整页的笔记，

95
00:04:47.220 --> 00:04:49.116
noting that I was impulsive,
上面写着我极易冲动，

96
00:04:49.140 --> 00:04:50.876
had a short attention span,
注意力难以集中，

97
00:04:50.900 --> 00:04:52.996
and despite my wonderful curiosity,
虽然拥有极大的好奇心，

98
00:04:53.020 --> 00:04:55.036
I was exhausting to work with.
但却是一个使人筋疲力尽的孩子。

99
00:04:55.060 --> 00:04:56.660
(Laughter)
（笑声）

100
00:04:57.820 --> 00:05:00.676
The principal asked my parents into a meeting,
校长叫我的家长们来开会，

101
00:05:00.700 --> 00:05:03.556
asked my mother if there had been complications at birth
问我妈生我的时候 有没有遇到什么困难，

102
00:05:03.580 --> 00:05:06.556
and suggested I meet with a school psychologist.
还建议我去看学校的心理医生。

103
00:05:06.580 --> 00:05:08.156
My father saw what was happening
我的父亲明白了是怎么一回事，

104
00:05:08.180 --> 00:05:10.260
and quickly explained our family situation.
并简短的解释了我们家的情况。

105
00:05:11.140 --> 00:05:13.596
As recent immigrants, we lived in the attic
作为刚刚移民的家庭，

106
00:05:13.620 --> 00:05:16.620
of a home that cared for adults with mental disabilities.
我们住在一家老年 康复中心的阁楼里。

107
00:05:17.140 --> 00:05:19.436
My parents worked nights to make ends meet,
我的父母为了维持生计 整日整夜工作，

108
00:05:19.460 --> 00:05:22.500
and I had little opportunity to spend time with kids my own age.
而我也几乎没有和 同龄孩子玩耍的机会。

109
00:05:23.700 --> 00:05:27.356
Is it really a surprise that an understimulated five-year-old boy
对于一个交际经验不足，又刚刚独处了 整整一个夏天的五岁小男孩来说，

110
00:05:27.380 --> 00:05:29.916
might be a little excited in a kindergarten classroom
在幼儿园的教室里 显得有些过度兴奋，

111
00:05:29.940 --> 00:05:31.700
after an entire summer by himself?
也许不显得那么令人惊讶吧？

112
00:05:32.980 --> 00:05:36.236
Until we get a holistic view of someone,
在我们没有看到一个人 完整的一面的时候，

113
00:05:36.260 --> 00:05:39.540
our judgment of them will always be flawed.
我们对他的评判总是有失偏颇的。

114
00:05:40.740 --> 00:05:44.876
Let's stop equating experience with ability,
让我们别再把经历和能力划等号，

115
00:05:44.900 --> 00:05:46.700
credentials with competence.
也别把文凭和竞争力划等号。

116
00:05:47.540 --> 00:05:50.916
Let's stop settling for the safe, familiar choice
让我们不要再一昧的做出 安全，熟悉的选择，

117
00:05:50.940 --> 00:05:53.900
and leave the door open for someone who could be amazing.
而是把机会给予那些 能够让你眼前一亮的人。

118
00:05:55.340 --> 00:05:58.596
We need employers to let go of outdated hiring practices
我们需要让雇主们放弃 那些过时的雇佣政策，

119
00:05:58.620 --> 00:06:02.180
and embrace new ways of identifying and cultivating talent,
去拥抱那些定义和 培养天赋的新方法，

120
00:06:02.900 --> 00:06:05.996
and candidates can help by learning to tell their story
而求职者们也可以通过 用强势且引人注目的方式，

121
00:06:06.020 --> 00:06:07.580
in powerful and compelling ways.
来讲述自己的人生故事。

122
00:06:08.740 --> 00:06:12.540
We could live in a world where people are seen for what they're truly capable of
我们会生活在全新的世界里，在那里 人们的潜力将有望被完全激发，

123
00:06:13.460 --> 00:06:16.900
and have the opportunity to realize their full potential.
人人都能够做自己真正胜任的工作。

124
00:06:18.140 --> 00:06:20.100
So let's go out and build it.
所以让我们一起携手建造这个世界吧。

125
00:06:20.860 --> 00:06:22.276
Thank you.
谢谢。

126
00:06:22.300 --> 00:06:29.060
(Applause)
（掌声）